Null value check 
SELECT COUNT(*) FROM sales WHERE customer_id IS NULL;
-No null value found 

Duplicate Detection
-Identified duplicate product entries to understand data repetition patterns.
SELECT product_id, COUNT(*)
FROM sales
GROUP BY product_id
HAVING COUNT(*) > 1;

duplicate validation
select * from sales where customer_04id ='DV-135';
-Duplicates were reviewed and confirmed as legitimate business records

The table did not contain a unique identifier.
-A surrogate primary key was added to uniquely identify each record and support Power BI relationships.

alter table sales 
Add column unique_id serial primary key;

Exact Duplicate Removal
-Removed only exact duplicate rows based on key transactional columns, while preserving genuine records.

DELETE FROM sales a
USING sales b
WHERE a.unique_id > b.unique_id
  AND a.product_id = b.product_id
  AND a.customer_id = b.customer_id
  AND a.sales = b.sales
  AND a.discount = b.discount
  AND a.profit = b.profit;

Invalid Value Check
SELECT * FROM sales WHERE quantity <= 0 OR sales <= 0;

Data type check 
SELECT column_name, data_type
FROM information_schema.columns
WHERE table_name = 'sales';
